{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649118","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649118"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:02:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:02:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18350"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18350"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.15,0.05,0.65,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11068"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74332"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11068"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18350"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59823"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7472"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25672"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25675"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74332","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74332"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following muscles is not a part of the first layer of the plantar muscles of the foot?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Abductor hallucis","Flexor digitorum brevis","Abductor digiti minimi","Quadratus plantae","Flexor hallucis brevis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe plantar muscles of the foot are organised into four layers, each containing specific muscles that contribute to foot movement and stability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Equadratus plantae\u003C/strong\u003E is not part of the first layer of the plantar muscles. It is located in the second layer, along with the lumbricals. The first layer includes the \u003Cstrong\u003Eabductor hallucis\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor digitorum brevis\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eabductor digiti minimi\u003C/strong\u003E. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eflexor hallucis brevis\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the third layer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The first layer of plantar muscles in the foot includes the abductor hallucis, flexor digitorum brevis, and abductor digiti minimi.","The lumbricals are part of the second layer of plantar muscles in the foot.","Understanding the layers of plantar muscles is important for diagnosing and treating foot-related conditions."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59823"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18350"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59823","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions